[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "S:K63.AT5.A762.A75 AQJ974..KQJ3.J83 85.QJ97642.9.K94 T2.K83.T854.QT62"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "4H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "S"]
1NT 2S 4H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 1, chOption: N, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:0, nBasis: 2, nRot: 2, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "ffc5f566bf2cfff6e1724bb5cb8e2bfb5a69eaa44f7e30d3781a186fe19c78af"]
[Category "Practice Deals"]
[Difficulty "mixed"]
[SkillPath "practice_deals/100_notrump"]
[Student "S"]
{You would really like to have a transfer bid in this situation, to make South bid \Hs.

But you don't have one, so you just bid 4\H yourself.

North plays 4\H. East leads the \ST. You play low in dummy and East holds the trick. He continues the suit and West takes the \SQ and then plays the \SA.

Loser List: \S = 2 : \H = 1 : \D = 0 : \C = 1 :: Total = 4

You've already lost the 2 \Ss. If East has the \HK you might avoid a loser there. You don't have a winner on which to discard the \C loser. 

If West has the \HK it will have to be a singleton to help you, so it is more logical to play East for the \HK.  But if East does have the \HK it will do you no good to ruff West's \SA, East will over-ruff and you would still have that \C loser. 

So do it this way instead. Discard the \C loser on West's \SA! Another \S from West won't hurt you since dummy would be able to over-ruff East. Whatever West plays you can win, then finesse East out of his \HK.

It was said earlier that you didn't have a winner on which you could discard the \C loser.

That was true, so instead you were able to discard it on a loser! }
[Play "W"]ST

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:AQJT.A65.AQ85.KT 92.JT982.94.A976 753.Q3.KJ62.8542 K864.K74.T73.QJ3"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "3NT"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
2NT pass 3NT pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "1fe2a28a338bfdeb1be4d8a2dc7e1e086cb3c901e75a47fb1c811b509905c59f"]
[Category "Practice Deals"]
[Difficulty "mixed"]
[SkillPath "practice_deals/100_notrump"]
[Student "S"]
{With 20 HCP and balanced distribution you should open 2NT. Do not let the good 4-card \S suit sway you to anything else. Partner bids 3NT and everybody passes.

East plays 3NT. South leads the \HJ. You try the \HQ, but North plays the \HK.

Winner List: \S = 1 : \H = 0 : \D = 4 : \C = 1 :: Total = 6

You need 3 more winners and at least 2 of them must come from \Ss. Furthermore you don't want North to lead \Cs through your King. Your best hope is that North holds the \SK so you can finesse.  

So you win the \HA and start thinking about dummy entries. Your obvious entries are the \DK and \DJ. If North holds only two small \Ss with his \SK, then two entries will be enough. But what if North holds \S K x x x ? Can you find a third entry to dummy? 

If the \Ds split 3-2 the answer is <b>YES</b>. Play the \DA, then lead your \D8 to dummy's \DJ. Watch carefully to see if both defenders follow to this trick. They do. Play a \S to your \ST, which holds the trick. Play your \DQ to dummy's \DK. Finesse the \S again. Return to dummy by playing your \D5 to dummy's \D6, then finesse the \S one last time.

If the \Ds had split 4-1 you would not have been able to enter dummy three times. That would have been very unlucky.

If you played your \D5 too early you would not have been able to enter dummy three times even when there was a 3-2 split. That would have been very unsmart.}
[Play "W"]HJ

